Communications delays due to the speed of light happen with communication with the moon at 1/4 million miles away & beyond, or Mars at millions of miles away.Not at low earth orbit. The speed of light is 186,000 miles per second. The diameter of earth is a little over 7,000 miles. The world is about 25,000 miles in circumference at the equator. Most satellites orbit under 400 miles high.

The delay is due to digital communication. The media is converted to code, then to ones & zeros, then converted to pulses or beeps to be transmitted through the internet or communication system. It may also have to be converted to another digital language for the satellite. From the satellite, it has to be converted to another digital language to be sent back down the internet. To reduce signal loss over the distances, the digital signal is received at hubs along the way & re-transmitted.

When you get the digital signal, your devices convert it back into something they can read, & display or play on your screen & speakers.

Place a cheap older & expensive newer TV next to each other tuned into the same channel. You will see one TV will be delayed more than the other, & hear an echo delay. At only a few inches apart & the speed of light being 186,000 miles per second, the delay is not because of the speed of light, but because of the speed of processing he data.

I have a question, I'm sure someone smarter than me has thought of this already... Would it be possible to launch rockets off the ground with the use of a roller track system? Something like a roller coaster. Imagine a long roller track in the dessert, this track would have a slow ramp from horizontal to vertical. The rocket itself would be mounted on multiple coasters to allow for the curved path and not distort the shape of the solid rocket. To propel all this weight, use electro magnetic rail system to begin moving all this mass which I believe is the most demanding stage of lift off. Once the rail is moving fast enough have the rockets engage and take over and once rocket is vertical detach from the coasters and proceed into space. It would also be a good idea to have a solar panel plant to build charge  over time to power the electro magnetic rail system. i just moved in to a house on merritt island about a week before this launch (my house is approximately 10-15 minutes away from kennedy space center, give or take a few) and this was the first launch i've experienced since living here. in case anyone was wondering what it's like for the falcon heavy to be launched essentially in your backyard at 2:30 am, it definitely woke me the hell up. our roof is tin, so the initial launch essentially sounded like incredibly close and heavy thunder that just went on for a straight minute or so. the roof and windows rattled as well as the walls. i'm a florida native, so i'm used to sounds similar to that from the really bad storms (not as prolonged of course; almost like the thunder was holding a note for a whole minute) and the takeoff itself didn't really scare me. the scariest part was the sonic booms that came afterwards. the only way i can think of to describe it was like a giant randomly coming up and kicking and punching my house or a full on giant cannonball getting shot at the house twice in a row.

They were doing 3 engine landing burn to arrest the higher reentry speed, this probably also means it was harder to control / time it. If the suicide burn was bit early / too strong the center core reached zero vertical speed while still several feet above the deck. Since a near empty Falcon9 is not able to make a powered descent - empty weight being lower than the minimum thrust of a single engine - the options were either to shut down the engines and drop the core on the deck from several feet above or ascend under power and ditch to the side. List of all my favorite moments (mostly fireworks):
1. Liftoff
2. Seeing the rocket barely illuminated by the engines on the way up.
3. The center core's flame washing over the boosters on separation.
4. Infrared camera showing boosters floating away in the center core's plume and then igniting.
5. They way the plasma dances between the center core and the boosters blasting at each-other on their on-board cameras.
6. The 3 stages of startup on the vacuum optimized engine (unlit, mixed propellants blasted out the back by just the turbo-pumps ... sustained green flash ... bright white flare of ignition)
7. Upper stage pelting the center core with flame as it speeds off.
8. Infrared images of the booster coming down and lighting up.
9. Dat booster landing tho
10. Fireworks show as the center core goes out with a bang.


Runners up:
- Expanding plume as the rocket ascends into a vacuum
- The fact that you can see the center core shut down and the upper stage start up through.
- The blanket of light between the left and right booster where their exhausts interact when they're far enough away from the center core that it's only the two of them left flying back together.
- OCISLY deck lights seeming to dim as the camera adjust for the brightness of the incoming rocket flare.
- edit: caught a fairing!!! (runner up because we didn't get to see it caught live.)
